This notebook will pilot a bunch of methods ot analyse loud overlapping CF-FM calls. I think it should be possible to put together something which works and is not too complicated just using whatever it is that I've already coded up. Let's see.

Idea 1: Analyse ACTUAL overlapping calls (abandoned)¶

This idea has been sketched out in the first part of this notebook - and isn't as straightforward as I had imagined. It might need some more work I think.

Idea 2: Analyse call sequences Jump to Idea 2 implementation¶

This is idea isn't strictly in line with the main idea of the notebook - but I realised I could essentially use the fact that we have call sequences to figure out a bunch of things. The 50ms approach is too .... non-contextual I feel. Analysing entire call sequences will allow a closer contextual look eg. access to call durations, inter-pulse intervals, and duty cycle in single bat call scenarios and eg. a 'duty-cycle' also in multi-bat scenarios.

  • Duty cycle estimation : I realised what I CAN do fairly easily and in a somewhat robust manner is to compare the duty cycles of the audio sequences. The duty cycle is estimated in the following manner:

    1. Load audio
    2. Determine channel with highest RMS - called the 'loudest channel'
    3. Calculate RMS profile of loudest channel with a 1ms window size
    4. Identify contiguous regions above a user-defined dBrms threshold. Discard any segments shorter than 10ms as they are unlikely to be full calls
    5. Calculate duty cycle by $\frac{\Sigma Region \:durations \geq \:threshold}{Total \:audio \:duration}$

The actual user-set threshold will be important in deciding the results of the analysis - and so it can be repeated at multiple values.

Idea 2¶

This section will study the call duty cycle of the bats. While the standard duty cycle measurements perhaps rely on high SNR lab-recorded or field recorded audio, we must do with what we have. The duty cycle measurements will definitely be affected by reverberation very strongly - and so I've done the same duty cycle analysis using two thresholds to define call segments - one liberal and one conservative.

def get_loudest_channel(X, channels=[0,1,2]):
    rms = np.zeros(len(channels))
    for i,each in enumerate(channels):
        rms[i] = itsfm.signal_processing.rms(X[:,each])
    loudest_channel = np.argmax(rms)
    return loudest_channel, rms
def filter_segments_by_duration(detections, fs, **kwargs):
    '''
    Parameters
    ----------
    detections: list with slices
    fs : float>0
        Frequency of sampling in Hz
    min_duration : float, optional 
        The minimum duration a slice must be to be kept in the final list.
        Defaults to 0.01 s.
    Returns
    -------
    geq_minduration : list with slices
        A list with slices that are greater or equal to the minimum duration. 
    '''
    durations = [float((each[0].stop-each[0].start)/fs) for each in detections]
    geq_minduration = []
    for detection, seg_durn in zip(detections,durations):
        if seg_durn >= kwargs.get('min_duration',0.01):
            geq_minduration.append(detection)
    return geq_minduration 

def overall_duty_cycle(detections, audio):
    '''
    Calculates the 'ON' fraction by summing the druation of all detections and 
    dividing it by the total duration of the audio. 
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    detections: list with slices
    audio: np.array

    Returns
    -------
    overall_duty_cycle
    
    Notes
    -----
    This is different from the 'duty cycle' typically used in high-duty cycle 
    bat echolocation eg. in Fenton, Faure, Ratcliffe 2012 (JEB)
    
    References
    ----------
    Fenton, M. B., Faure, P. A., & Ratcliffe, J. M. (2012). Evolution of high duty cycle echolocation in bats.
    Journal of Experimental Biology, 215(17), 2935-2944.
    
    '''
    total_on_samples = 0
    for each in detections:
        total_on_samples += each[0].stop-each[0].start
    try:
        assert (audio.shape[1] ==1), "Audio can only have 1 channel for duty cycle calculation"
    except:
        pass
    
    overall_duty_cycle = total_on_samples/float(audio.size)
    return overall_duty_cycle

from scipy import ndimage
# thanks to @matehat (https://stackoverflow.com/a/8260297/4955732)
def window_rms(a, window_size):
  a2 = np.power(a,2)
  window = np.ones(window_size)/float(window_size)
  return np.sqrt(np.convolve(a2, window, 'valid'))

def fast_find_geq_signallevel(X,fs, **kwargs):
    '''
    Modified from itsfm.frequency_tracking.find_geq_signallevel
    '''
    signal_level = kwargs.get('signal_level', -20)
    winsize = kwargs.get('window_size', int(fs*0.002))
    rec_level = dB(window_rms(X, winsize))
    
    ids_above_noise, num_regions = ndimage.label(rec_level>signal_level)
    if num_regions <1:
        raise ValueError('No regions above signal level found!')

    return ndimage.find_objects(ids_above_noise), rec_level

def calculate_dutycycle_by_groupsize(filenamesbygroupsize, filecolname,
                                     signal_threshold, audio_folder,groupsizes=[4,3,2,1],
                                      **kwargs):
    '''
    Parameters
    ----------
    
    
    
    min_duration : float, optional 
        Defaults to 10ms
    
    Returns
    -------
    
    '''
    dutycycle_by_groupsize = {}
    
    for groupsize in groupsizes:
        all_files = filenamesbygroupsize.get_group(groupsize)
        dutycycle_by_groupsize[groupsize] = []
        for each in all_files[filecolname]:
            filepath = ca2.find_file_in_folder(each, audio_folder)[0]
            if sf.info(filepath).channels>1:
                audio, fs = sf.read(filepath)
                loud_ch, channel_rms = get_loudest_channel(audio)
                audio = audio[:,loud_ch]
            else:
                audio, fs = sf.read(filepath)
            window_size = kwargs.get('window_size',int(fs*0.001))
            try:
                print('miaow')
                above_level, rms_profile = fast_find_geq_signallevel(audio, fs,
                                                                     window_size=window_size,
                                                                     signal_level=signal_threshold)
                longish_detns = filter_segments_by_duration(above_level, fs, **kwargs)
                odc = overall_duty_cycle(longish_detns, audio)
                dutycycle_by_groupsize[groupsize].append(odc)
            except:
                pass
            
    return dutycycle_by_groupsize

The effect of signal threshold on the duty cycle calculations¶

Figure caption: The audio duty cycle, defined as the fraction of time occupied by calls in an audio recording across group sizes in observed and virtual multi-bat audio. The duty cycle was calculated across group sizes using two thresholds to detect calls. A) The duty cycle across group size in observed and virtual audio with the liberal threshold (-47 dBrms) set at +10dBrms above the background level B) Duty cycle across observed and virtual audio with a conservative threshold (-37 dBrms) set at +20 dB rms above the background level. Virtual multi-bat audio was created by adding duration-matched single bat audio files. Both A) and B) show a similar trend with a general increased duty cycle in multi-bat comparison to single bat audio. The 95 percentile ranges of duty cycles in observed and virtual audio overlap across group sizes 2-4. This overlap indicates that bats may not decreasing or increasing their call duty cycle in the presence of others.

Are the call duties much higher than expected by chance from single bat call duties?¶

If the bats are indeed not showing drastic responses (increased or decreased) to each other, the duty cycles should be broadly the same as calculated from assuming single bat duty cycles hold

In [37]:
## The 2 bat case

def calc_prob_nonexclusive_events(probs):
    '''
    Calculates the probability of co-occurence of multiple non-mutually exclusive events. 
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    probs : list/array-like 
        All values must be between 0-1. Each probability value corresponds to the 
        probability of one event type occuring. 

   
    '''
    if len(probs)==2:
        A,B = probs
        return A + B - A*B
    elif len(probs) == 3:
        A,B,C = probs
        return A + B + C - A*B - B*C - A*C + A*B*C
    else:
        raise ValueError('0 or 4 events not supported')

The observed multi bat median call duties closely match the calculated 2 and 3 bat call duties. The calculations assume independent call behaviour. For example:

  • 2 bat observe call duty is 0.226 and calculated is 0.228
  • 3 bat observed call duty is 0.336 and calculated is 0.321

Two lines of evidence suggest no change in call duty in the presence of conspecifics¶

  1. Overlap of call duties in multi-bat observed and virtual audio recordings.
  2. Close match between observed multi-bat call duties and calculated call-duties assuming independence of events.

# observed data
obs_dataset = []

for threshold in [-37, -47]:
    for groupsize in [1,2,3,4]:
        obs_dutycycle = dutycyles_by_threshold[threshold][0][groupsize]
        gpsize = np.tile(groupsize, len(obs_dutycycle))
        scenario = np.tile('obs', len(obs_dutycycle))
        df = pd.DataFrame(data={'groupsize':gpsize,
                                'duty_cycle':obs_dutycycle,
                                'audio_type': scenario})
        df['threshold_dbrms'] = threshold
        obs_dataset.append(df)
        
obs_dataset = pd.concat(obs_dataset)

# virtual audio data
virt_dataset = []

for threshold in [-37, -47]:
    for groupsize in [2,3,4]:
        obs_dutycycle = dutycyles_by_threshold[threshold][1][groupsize]
        gpsize = np.tile(groupsize, len(obs_dutycycle))
        scenario = np.tile('virtual', len(obs_dutycycle))
        df = pd.DataFrame(data={'groupsize':gpsize,
                                'duty_cycle':obs_dutycycle,
                                'audio_type': scenario})
        df['threshold_dbrms'] = threshold
        virt_dataset.append(df)
        
virt_dataset = pd.concat(virt_dataset)
